@online{vanDerAalst2026,
    primaryclass = {},
    url = {https://www.linkedin.com/posts/wvdaalst_academicintegrity-generativeai-science-activity-7435761906608570368-_oLj},
    archiveprefix = {LinkedIn},
    author = {van der Aalst, Wil},
    year = {2026},
    title = {When Generative AI Meets/Destroys Academic Integrity},
    abstract = {Today I encountered something disturbing: a fake paper uploaded to ResearchGate listing me as an author, even though I had nothing to do with it. Another respected colleague (Jan vom Brocke), who was listed as well, found the fake paper. Neither of us had any involvement.

Generative AI has made it trivially easy to produce plausible-looking scientific papers. Titles, abstracts, references, and even figures can now be generated in seconds. Combined with platforms that automatically index and distribute publications, this opens the door to new forms of academic spam and fraud.

For decades, science has relied heavily on trust and community norms. We assumed that most publications were created in good faith. Generative AI challenges this assumption by dramatically lowering the cost of producing convincing but meaningless scientific content.

It is about protecting the integrity of science.

If AI can generate thousands of papers overnight, the real bottleneck will no longer be writing papers—it will be knowing which ones to trust.

In the coming years, safeguarding scientific credibility may become one of the most important challenges for academia. Conferences where communities actually meet are more important than ever.

------

I guess the goal is to create papers with the names of other established authors on them, citing their own paper. In this particular example, I noted four citations to real papers unrelated to the topic of the fake paper and not cited in the text. Of these four citations, three included the same author, but this is not the person uploading the paper to ResearchGate. So the trick is: create a fake identity on ResearchGate, generate fake papers with the names of other authors and the fake identity, add references to your own paper to these fake papers. It should be easy for ResearchGate to pick this up, but they do not seem to care. It is also hard to report.},
}

